=== 影響 ===
Among the students who studied with Richter at the Kunstakademie Düsseldorf between 1971 and 1994 were Ludger Gerdes, Hans-Jörg Holubitschka, Bernard Lokai, Thomas Schütte, Thomas Struth, Katrin Kneffel, Michael van Ofen, and Richter's second wife, Isa Genzken. He is known to have influenced Ellsworth Kelly, Christopher Wool, Allan Banford and  Johan Andersson.

He also served as source of inspiration for writers and musicians. [[音速青春|Sonic Youth]] used a painting of his for the cover art for their album ''Daydream Nation'' in 1988. He was a fan of the band and did not charge for the use of his image.{{Fact|date=October 2011}} The original, over {{Convert|7|m}} square, is now showcased in Sonic Youth's studio in NYC.{{Fact|date=October 2013}} [[堂·德里罗|Don DeLillo]]'s short story "Baader-Meinhof" describes an encounter between two strangers at the Museum of Modern Art in New York. The meeting takes place in the room displaying ''18 October 1977'' (1988).<ref>Don DeLillo (17 August 2002) [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/aug/17/fiction.originalwriting "Baader-Meinhof"] {{Wayback|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/aug/17/fiction.originalwriting |date=20160307173107 }} ''The Guardian''; Gordon Burn (20 September 2008), [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/sep/20/art1 "I believe in nothing"] {{Wayback|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2008/sep/20/art1 |date=20160313101121 }}, ''The Guardian''</ref>

Photographer Cotton Coulson described Richter as "one of [his] artists"<ref name="WPO">[http://www.worldphoto.org/news-and-events/wpo-news/national-geographic-traveller-cotton-coulson/ National Geographic Traveller: Cotton Coulson]{{dead link|date=十月 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}, at the [//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Photographic_Organisation World Photographic Organisation]; published December 10, 2014; retrieved June 21, 2015</ref>

=== 藝術市場定位 ===
Following an exhibition with Blinky Palermo at Galerie Heiner Friedrich in 1971, Richter's formal arrangement with the dealer came to an end in 1972. Thereafter Friedrich was only entitled to sell the paintings that he had already obtained contractually from Richter. In the following years, Richter showed with Galerie Konrad Fischer, Düsseldorf, and Sperone Westwater, New York. Today Richter is represented by Marian Goodman,<ref>[http://www.mariangoodman.com/artists/gerhard-richter/ Gerhard Richter] {{Wayback|url=http://www.mariangoodman.com/artists/gerhard-richter/ |date=20101022055914 }} Marian Goodman Gallery</ref> his primary dealer since 1985.

Today, museums own roughly 38% of Richter's works, including half of his large abstract paintings. By 2004, Richter's annual turnover was $120 million.<ref>Roger Boyes (June 17, 2006), [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article675615.ece Nazi ghosts haunting a family] {{Wayback|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article675615.ece |date=20090521121452 }} ''[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Times The Times]''</ref> At the same time, his works often appear at auction. According to artnet, an online firm that tracks the art market, $76.9 million worth of Richter's work was sold at auction in 2010. Richter's high turnover volume reflects his prolificacy as well as his popularity. As of 2012, no fewer than 545 distinct Richter's works had sold at auctions for more than $100,000. 15 of them had sold for more than $10,000,000 between 2007 and 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/felix-salmon/2012/03/04/the-commodification-of-gerhard-richter/|title=The commodification of Gerhard Richter|work=Reuters|accessdate=2017-01-27|archive-date=2012-03-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306235322/http://blogs.reuters.com/felix-salmon/2012/03/04/the-commodification-of-gerhard-richter/|dead-url=no}}</ref> Richter's paintings have been flowing steadily out of Germany since the mid-1990s even as certain important German collectors – Frieder Burda, Josef Fröhlich, Georg Böckmann, and Ulrich Ströher – have held on to theirs.

Richter's candle paintings were the first to command high auction prices. Three months after his MoMA exhibition opened in 2001, [[蘇富比|Sotheby's]] sold his ''Three Candles'' (1982) for $5.3 million. In February 2008, the artist's eldest daughter, Betty, sold her ''Kerze'' (1983) for £7,972,500 ($15 million), triple the high estimate, at Sotheby's in London.<ref>[http://www.sothebys.com/app/live/lot/LotDetail.jsp?lot_id=159429721 Gerhard Richter b. 1932, ''Kerze'' (Candle), Sale: L08020] Sotheby's London, Contemporary Art Evening Auction, 27 February 2008</ref> His 1982 ''Kerze (Candle)'' sold for £10.5 million ($16.5 million) at [[佳士得|Christie's]] London in October 2011.<ref>Scott Reyburn (October 14, 2011), [http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-14/richter-candle-painting-fetches-record-16-6-million-at-christie-s-london.html Richter $16.6 Million Record Leads Auction Boost to Art Market] {{Wayback|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-14/richter-candle-painting-fetches-record-16-6-million-at-christie-s-london.html |date=20131206092418 }} ''[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloomberg_News Bloomberg News]''</ref>

In February 2008, Christie's London set a first record for Richter's "capitalist realism" pictures from the 1960s by selling the painting ''Zwei Liebespaare'' (1966) for £7,300,500 ($14.3 million)<ref>[http://www.christies.com/LotFinder/lot_details.aspx?intObjectID=5037909 Gerhard Richter (b. 1932) ''Zwei Liebespaare'', Sale 7565] {{Wayback|url=http://www.christies.com/LotFinder/lot_details.aspx?intObjectID=5037909 |date=20121023193013 }} Christie's London, Post-War and Contemporary Art Evening Sale, 6 February 2008</ref> to Stephan Schmidheiny. In 2010, the Weserburg modern art museum in Bremen, Germany, decided to sell Richter's 1966 painting ''Matrosen'' (Sailors) in a November auction held by Sotheby's, where John D. Arnold bought it for $13 million.<ref name="matrosen">[http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2010/contemporary-art-evening-auction-n08678/lot.36.html Gerhard Richter, b.1932: Matrosen (Sailors)] {{Wayback|url=http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/2010/contemporary-art-evening-auction-n08678/lot.36.html |date=20150924125934 }}.</ref> ''Vierwaldstätter See'', the largest of a distinct series of four views of [[琉森湖|Lake Lucerne]] painted by Richter in 1969, sold for £15.8 million ($24 million) at [[佳士得|Christie's]] London in 2015.<ref>Scott Reyburn (February 12, 2015), [http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/13/arts/design/christies-and-sothebys-auctions-in-london-keep-the-bubble-afloat.html Christie's and Sotheby's Auctions in London Keep the Bubble Afloat] {{Wayback|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/13/arts/design/christies-and-sothebys-auctions-in-london-keep-the-bubble-afloat.html |date=20201108122743 }} ''[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_York_Times The New York Times]''</ref>

Another coveted group of works is the ''Abstrakte Bilder'' series, particularly those made after 1988, which are finished with a large squeegee rather than a brush or roller. At [[貝爾傑|Pierre Bergé]] & Associés in July 2009, Richter's 1979 oil painting ''Abstraktes Bild'' exceeded its estimate, selling for €95,000 ($136,000).<ref name="bild447">[http://www.gerhard-richter.com/art/search/detail.php?paintid=6248&number=447&p=1&sp=32 Abstraktes Bild – Abstract Painting 1979: Catalogue Raisonné 447]. </ref> Richter's ''Abstraktes Bild'', of 1990 was made the top price of 7.2 million pounds, or about $11.6 million, at a Sotheby's sale in February 2011 to a bidder who was said by dealers to be an agent for the New York dealer Larry Gagosian.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/17/arts/17iht-Melik17.html|title=Disruptions at Sotheby's Contemporary Auction|last=Souren Melikian|date=February 16, 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2017-01-27|archive-date=2019-11-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103121709/https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/17/arts/17iht-Melik17.html|dead-url=no}}</ref> In November 2011, Sotheby's sold a group of colorful abstract canvases by Richter, including ''Abstraktes Bild 849-3'', which made a record price for the artist at auction when Lily Safra<ref name="Vogel">Carol Vogel (January 12, 2012), [http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/arts/design/israel-museum-receiving-a-work-by-gerhard-richter.html?ref=design Surprise!] {{Wayback|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/13/arts/design/israel-museum-receiving-a-work-by-gerhard-richter.html?ref=design |date=20191203151857 }}</ref> paid $20.8 million<ref>Carol Vogel (November 9, 2011), [http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/10/arts/sothebys-contemporary-art-sale-totals-316-million.html?ref=design As Stocks Fall, Art Surges At a $315.8 Million Sale] {{Wayback|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/10/arts/sothebys-contemporary-art-sale-totals-316-million.html?ref=design |date=20191115001439 }}, ''[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_York_Times The New York Times]''</ref> only to donate it to the [[以色列博物館|Israel Museum]] afterwards. Months later, a record $21.8 million was paid at Christie's for the 1993 painting ''Abstraktes Bild 798-3''.<ref>Scott Reyburn (June 13, 2012), [http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-12/richter-twombly-lead-2-billion-basel-art-fair.html Hedge Funder Cohen, Eye Rothko, $25 Million Richter Sells] {{Wayback|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-12/richter-twombly-lead-2-billion-basel-art-fair.html |date=20140525082921 }} ''Bloomberg''</ref> ''Abstraktes Bild (809-4)'', one of the artist's abstract canvases from 1994, was sold by [[埃里克·克莱普顿|Eric Clapton]] at Sotheby's to a telephone bidder for $34.2 million in late 2012. (It had been estimated to bring $14.1 million to $18.8 million.<ref>Carol Vogel (October 15, 2012), [http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/10/15/gerhard-richter-painting-sets-record-auction-price-for-a-living-artist/ Gerhard Richter Painting Sets Record Auction Price for a Living Artist] {{Wayback|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/10/15/gerhard-richter-painting-sets-record-auction-price-for-a-living-artist/ |date=20130518074300 }}, ''[//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_York_Times The New York Times]''</ref> When asked about amounts like that Richter said "It's just as absurd as the [[2007年–2008年環球金融危機|banking crisis]]. It's impossible to understand and it's [[wiktionary:daft|daft]]!"<ref name="phaidon1">[http://www.phaidon.co.uk/agenda/art/events/2011/october/06/gerhard-richter-talks-about-panorama-at-tate-modern/ "Gerhard Richter talks about Panorama at Tate Modern"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009091002/http://www.phaidon.co.uk/agenda/art/events/2011/october/06/gerhard-richter-talks-about-panorama-at-tate-modern/ |date=2011-10-09 }}, Phaidon.com, October 2011 Error in webarchive template: Check <code style="color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;">|url=</code> value. 空的。
